709422f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, West side, looking north between 32nd and 33rd Streets, showing Manhattan Theatre, Trainor's Hotel, and Saks Thirty-Fourth Street.
April 1909.
Brown Brothers, Photographers.

709423f-a.text:
Manhattan Theatre, Gane's Moving Picture House; Trainor's Hotel. View on Sixth Avenue north between 32nd and 33rd Streets. West side.
Mr Gane in front.
April 1909.
Photographed by Brown Brothers.

709421f-a.text:
Gimbels, Sixth Avenue, west side, from 32nd to 33rd Streets
1910.

709420f-a.text:
889 to 885 (old No. 533-529) Sixth Ave., at and adjoining the S.W. corner of West 32nd Street. The 4-story white building, new No. 885 (old No. 529) is Childs Restaurant. In the foreground, is Broadway.
April 22, 1929.
P. L. Sperr.

709424f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, west side, north from West 32nd Street. At this date the old "El" line has been demolished though the southbound station remains. This is at 33rd Street and provides an entrance to the two department stores here, Gimbels and Saks, through an enclosed bridgeway. After the amicable adjustment by these stores, the Hudson Tube officials, the City and the "El" line authorities, the station will be removed. Beyond same appears the dominant Herald Square Building.
View 1: March 29, 1939
View 2: April 5, 1939
P. L. Sperr

720144f-a.text:
Sixth Avenue, north from W. 32nd Street, showing Greeley Square; the southerly triangular area formed by Broadway intersecting 6th Avenue. The "El" follows the latter and the Potel McAloin (right) is on the former. To the left are Gimbels and Saks Dept. Stores. The first mentioned does not appear. Above the "El" station (demolished in 1938-9) towers the Herald Scuare Building.
Broadway is to the left.
View 1: December 24, 1936
View 2: April 22, 1929
View 3: April 15, 1940
P. L. Sperr
